But they're excited more if
the temperature of the universe

01:10:33.540 --> 01:10:36.730
were slightly higher
than the current 2.7.

01:10:36.730 --> 01:10:41.630
So astronomers looked at
these clouds at redshift 1,

01:10:41.630 --> 01:10:43.180
when by the way the
temperature would

01:10:43.180 --> 01:10:47.830
have been 5.4-- 1 plus z times
the current temperature--

01:10:47.830 --> 01:10:52.400
and lo and behold, the
transitions were clearly

01:10:52.400 --> 01:10:55.530
stronger back then, because
the absorption lines produced

01:10:55.530 --> 01:10:59.590
by those clouds of gas were
stronger than would have been

01:10:59.590 --> 01:11:03.060
the case had the temperature
back then been 2.7.

01:11:03.060 --> 01:11:06.440
So in fact, we've measured not
only the microwave background,

01:11:06.440 --> 01:11:08.530
but changes in its temperature.

01:11:08.530 --> 01:11:11.770
What has not been
done is studies

01:11:11.770 --> 01:11:15.710
of enough molecular clouds
at a variety of redshifts

01:11:15.710 --> 01:11:19.150
to see a transition in the rate
of change of the temperature.

01:11:19.150 --> 01:11:23.160
But in principle, I see no
reason that couldn't be done.

01:11:23.160 --> 01:11:24.730
That is very cool.

01:11:24.730 --> 01:11:26.740
You're the first-- I
can tell I'm at Google.

01:11:26.740 --> 01:11:29.200
You're the first
person ever, ever,

01:11:29.200 --> 01:11:30.570
to have asked me that question.

01:11:30.570 --> 01:11:35.150
So I feel like I'm on a
thesis exam or something

01:11:35.150 --> 01:11:37.500
here, where you have to
answer these kinds of things

01:11:37.500 --> 01:11:38.070
really well.

01:11:38.070 --> 01:11:39.380
Yeah.

01:11:39.380 --> 01:11:40.320
Other questions?

01:11:40.320 --> 01:11:43.190
Right there, yes.

01:11:43.190 --> 01:11:45.710
AUDIENCE: How do we
know the basic nature

01:11:45.710 --> 01:11:47.760
of the cosmic microwave
background that

01:11:47.760 --> 01:11:50.310
is coming from a
blast from the past,

01:11:50.310 --> 01:11:52.527
as opposed to, say,
the void glowing?

01:11:52.527 --> 01:11:53.860
DR. ALEX FILIPPENKO: Yeah, yeah.

01:11:53.860 --> 01:11:56.130
So various people
have tried to think

01:11:56.130 --> 01:12:00.310
of ways of reproducing
the microwave background

01:12:00.310 --> 01:12:02.020
radiation through local sources.

01:12:02.020 --> 01:12:05.200
And in fact, iron
whiskers, turns out,

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:10.210
radiate in a way that
has some good properties.

01:12:10.210 --> 01:12:18.630
You can't get a perfect
single temperature background

01:12:18.630 --> 01:12:24.490
if you've got objects at
different redshifts glowing,

01:12:24.490 --> 01:12:25.690
due to whatever process.

01:12:25.690 --> 01:12:28.180
You'd need to somehow
finagle them all

01:12:28.180 --> 01:12:32.030
to have a slightly different
intrinsic spectrum, such

01:12:32.030 --> 01:12:34.180
that when you add
them all together

01:12:34.180 --> 01:12:36.820
at these different redshifts,
all their contributions,

01:12:36.820 --> 01:12:39.890
they end up giving
you a black body that

01:12:39.890 --> 01:12:43.900
is better than the thickness of
the pen with which you draw it.

01:12:43.900 --> 01:12:45.760
That's how good the data are.

01:12:45.760 --> 01:12:49.880
I mean, the measurements
from Coby and Planck

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:53.310
and the W map satellites
are absolutely perfect

01:12:53.310 --> 01:12:54.030
black bodies.

01:12:54.030 --> 01:12:56.670
And so we've thought of
no way of doing that.

01:12:56.670 --> 01:12:58.760
And yet, if the
universe did begin

01:12:58.760 --> 01:13:02.500
in a hot compressed state, for
which we have other evidence--

01:13:02.500 --> 01:13:05.500
primordial abundances
of hydrogen, deuterium,

01:13:05.500 --> 01:13:07.550
things like that
as well-- then you

01:13:07.550 --> 01:13:09.590
would expect this afterglow.

01:13:09.590 --> 01:13:13.120
Indeed, George Gamow and
his students and post-docs

01:13:13.120 --> 01:13:14.900
predicted it.

01:13:14.900 --> 01:13:18.290
So it's a natural prediction
of an expanding universe.

01:13:18.290 --> 01:13:20.750
And it's enormously
difficult and ad hoc

01:13:20.750 --> 01:13:23.890
to conjure up in any other way,
is what I would say, I guess.

01:13:23.890 --> 01:13:25.160
Yeah.

01:13:25.160 --> 01:13:28.910
AUDIENCE: So probably a naive
question about redshift.

01:13:28.910 --> 01:13:31.490
So the light waves
generate long ago

01:13:31.490 --> 01:13:34.760
because of the stretch of the
space got longer light wave.

01:13:34.760 --> 01:13:35.150
DR. ALEX FILIPPENKO:
That's right.

01:13:35.150 --> 01:13:36.160
AUDIENCE: Wavelengths.

01:13:36.160 --> 01:13:38.900
But when the space is
stretched, doesn't the rule

01:13:38.900 --> 01:13:41.840
for example, the way we measure
length, also get stretched?

01:13:41.840 --> 01:13:44.250
DR. ALEX FILIPPENKO: Yeah,
the lengths of the rulers

01:13:44.250 --> 01:13:46.640
are not stretched.

01:13:46.640 --> 01:13:49.571
Indeed we're not expanding.

01:13:49.571 --> 01:13:51.070
I mean, you might
after a big lunch,

01:13:51.070 --> 01:13:53.210
but that's your fault,
not the universe's fault.

01:13:53.210 --> 01:13:54.890
You're held by
electromagnetic forces.

01:13:54.890 --> 01:13:57.450
And again, it's a
spring that's so tight

01:13:57.450 --> 01:13:59.480
that you can't stretch it.

01:13:59.480 --> 01:14:01.910
We're held to the
earth by gravity

01:14:01.910 --> 01:14:03.280
in a way that's much greater.

01:14:03.280 --> 01:14:06.430
It easily overcomes the natural
tendency of space to expand.

01:14:06.430 --> 01:14:09.510
So even our local group of
galaxies is not expanding.

01:14:09.510 --> 01:14:12.360
Indeed, within it, Andromeda
is coming toward us.

01:14:12.360 --> 01:14:15.054
So if Hubble had only looked
at the Andromeda galaxy,

01:14:15.054 --> 01:14:17.470
he would have concluded that
the universe is collapsing in

01:14:17.470 --> 01:14:18.710
on itself.

01:14:18.710 --> 01:14:23.890
The expansion of space
is only visible starting,

01:14:23.890 --> 01:14:27.670
oh, 4 or 5 million
light years out.

01:14:27.670 --> 01:14:30.600
That's where the
density of material

01:14:30.600 --> 01:14:33.860
and the strength of
gravitational fields and things

01:14:33.860 --> 01:14:38.730
like that become low enough
that the stretching of space

01:14:38.730 --> 01:14:40.690
can start taking over.

01:14:40.690 --> 01:14:43.680
But we and the rulers
are not stretching.

01:14:43.680 --> 01:14:45.680
They're held together
by a spring that's

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:47.553
so tight that you
can't stretch it.

01:14:47.553 --> 01:14:50.330
AUDIENCE: Or can I say that
actually the stretch is there.

01:14:50.330 --> 01:14:52.600
It's just too small--
dominated by the other forces.

01:14:52.600 --> 01:14:54.480
DR. ALEX FILIPPENKO: Yeah,
the stretch is there.

01:14:54.480 --> 01:14:55.813
That's another way of saying it.

01:14:55.813 --> 01:14:57.900
But it's so overpowered
by the other forces

01:14:57.900 --> 01:15:01.070
that it's not noticeable.

01:15:01.070 --> 01:15:02.760
I'm very careful
to say it that way,

01:15:02.760 --> 01:15:05.380
because even in
some textbooks, you

01:15:05.380 --> 01:15:07.710
read the incorrect
statement that, oh yes,

01:15:07.710 --> 01:15:10.120
of course our
galaxy is expanding.

01:15:10.120 --> 01:15:14.010
But because our galaxy is only
100,000 light years across,

01:15:14.010 --> 01:15:17.190
if you put 100,000 light
years into Hubble's law,

01:15:17.190 --> 01:15:21.210
you get a negligible
amount of expansion.

01:15:21.210 --> 01:15:22.760
That is a wrong explanation.

01:15:22.760 --> 01:15:27.290
You cannot put 100,000 light
years into Hubble's law.

01:15:27.290 --> 01:15:30.860
Because that would imply
that our galaxy is stretching

01:15:30.860 --> 01:15:33.640
with the rest of the
universe unimpeded.

01:15:33.640 --> 01:15:34.510
And that's not true.

01:15:34.510 --> 01:15:38.700
It is being impeded
by its local gravity.

01:15:38.700 --> 01:15:39.939
So just watch out.

01:15:39.939 --> 01:15:41.230
There's that subtle difference.

01:15:41.230 --> 01:15:42.820
And I didn't want
you to walk away

01:15:42.820 --> 01:15:45.900
thinking that it's only
that our galaxy is small,

01:15:45.900 --> 01:15:48.400
and therefore you can't
notice the stretching

01:15:48.400 --> 01:15:50.680
over a distance of only
100,000 light years.

01:15:50.680 --> 01:15:51.620
It's more than that.

01:15:51.620 --> 01:15:54.410
It's that our galaxy impedes
the stretching because

01:15:54.410 --> 01:15:55.605
of its self-gravity.

01:15:55.605 --> 01:15:59.720
AUDIENCE: Light is
redshifted by the expansion,

01:15:59.720 --> 01:16:02.850
then it seems like that light
is going to be losing energy.

01:16:02.850 --> 01:16:04.200
Does that energy go somewhere?

01:16:04.200 --> 01:16:05.300
DR. ALEX FILIPPENKO: Ooh!

01:16:05.300 --> 01:16:06.420
Boy oh boy.

01:16:06.420 --> 01:16:08.910
The light is indeed
losing energy.

01:16:08.910 --> 01:16:10.590
That's right.

01:16:10.590 --> 01:16:14.450
Light has energy,
and therefore in fact

01:16:14.450 --> 01:16:15.650
has a gravitational effect.

01:16:15.650 --> 01:16:19.040
In fact, you could have a
black hole whose interior

01:16:19.040 --> 01:16:22.010
consists entirely
of light, before it

01:16:22.010 --> 01:16:23.740
went into the singularity
and got eaten.

01:16:23.740 --> 01:16:26.730
But you can imagine creating
a black hole out of light,

01:16:26.730 --> 01:16:31.160
because light has energy and
therefore it bends space-time.

01:16:31.160 --> 01:16:36.450
So in fact, what happens is,
in an expanding universe,

01:16:36.450 --> 01:16:39.510
the light itself-- forget about
anything else in the universe--

01:16:39.510 --> 01:16:42.730
the light itself is
impeding the expansion.

01:16:42.730 --> 01:16:46.910
The light is doing
work on the universe.

01:16:46.910 --> 01:16:51.850
And that is one way of thinking
of the redshifting of light.

01:16:51.850 --> 01:16:53.440
It is losing
energy, because it's

01:16:53.440 --> 01:16:55.511
doing work on the universe.

01:16:55.511 --> 01:16:56.510
Isn't that a cool thing?

01:16:56.510 --> 01:16:57.760
That's an interesting insight.

01:16:57.760 --> 01:16:59.590
Yeah.

01:16:59.590 --> 01:17:01.040
Very cool.

01:17:01.040 --> 01:17:04.144
And the universe is pretty
cool too, at 2.7 degrees now.

